                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>The United Nations Command, as the official military history of the Korean war
                    points out, was seriously handicapped in its discussions on item 4 at Panmunjom
                    by ignorance of the actual number of prisoners who would resist repatriation. In
                    mid-February, the Chief of the <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> Staff
                    estimated that approximately 16,000 of the 132,000 military prisoners and 30,000
                    of the 37,000 civilian internees held by the United Nations would resist
                    repatriation; see Hermes, <hi rend="italic">Truce Tent and Fighting Front</hi>,
                    pages 168–169. On March 17, <persName corresp="#p_RGMB1">Ridgway</persName>
                    reported to the Joint Chiefs of Staff that the latest, although highly
                    conjectural, estimate was that 73,000 persons including civilian internees,
                    might not elect to be <pb facs="0170" n="136" xml:id="pg_136"/> returned; see
                        <persName corresp="#p_RGMB1">Ridgway</persName> to <gloss target="#t_JCS1"
                        >JCS</gloss>, telegram CX 65424, March 17, <ref target="#pg_91">page
                        91</ref>. When the <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> and Communist staff
                    officers met in executive session at Panmunjom to discuss the prisoner of war
                    question, <persName corresp="#p_HCGWJ1">Colonel Hickman</persName> of the <gloss
                        target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> Staff observed to his Communist counterpart on
                    April 1 that possibly 116,000 persons would indicate “the magnitude of the
                    exchange” although the figure was by no means definite. On the next day, the
                    Communists suggested that debate on the <gloss target="#t_POWs1">POW</gloss>
                    question be deferred while both sides checked their lists and determined a
                    “round figure” of prisoners to be exchanged. A summary of these executive
                    sessions is in telegrams C 66228 and C 66285, <persName corresp="#p_RGMB1"
                        >Ridgway</persName> to <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>, April 1 and 2
                        (<gloss target="#t_FE1">FE</gloss> files, lot 55 D 128, tabs 7 and 9,
                    respectively).</p>
